snippet: Two camps in Cairo set up by supporters of the ousted Egyptian president, Mohamed Morsi, have become the front lines in a dangerous stalemate with the military-installed government.
abstract: Two protest camps in Cairo set up by supporters of ousted Egyptian Pres Mohamed Morsi are the front lines in the country's dangerous political stalemate with the military-installed government; military and police have already killed dozens of people, and human rights groups have reported cases in which Morsi’s supporters have detained and tortured opponents; but instead of scaring the protesters into going home, crackdowns have reinforced their conviction to stay.
lead_paragraph: Two camps in Cairo set up by supporters of the ousted Egyptian president, Mohamed Morsi, have become the front lines in a dangerous stalemate with the military-installed government.
